{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = <!--{{PAGENAME}} by default--> | synonym = | image = Keratic precipitate2.jpg | image_size = 120px | alt = | caption = Keratic precipitate due to Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada Disease | pronounce = | specialty = <!-- from Wikidata, can be overwritten --> | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Keratic precipitate''' ('''KP''') is an [[Inflammatory cell|inflammatory]] cellular deposit seen on [[corneal endothelium]]. Acute KPs are white and round in shape whereas old KPs are faded and irregular in shape. Mutton-fat KPs are large in shape and are greasy-white in color and are formed from [[macrophage]]s and [[epithelioid cell]]. They are indicative of inflammatory disease.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brightbill|first1=Frederick S.|title=Corneal Surgery: Theory, Technique and Tissue|date=2009|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=0323048358|page=102|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TbFyvZSx6W0C&dq=Keratic+precipitate&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=11 November 2017|language=en}}</ref> Mutton fat Kps are due to granulomatous iridocyclitis.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tandon|first1=Radhika|title=Parson's Diseases of the Eye - E-Book|date=2014|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=9788131238196|page=616|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JTJTBwAAQBAJ&dq=Keratic+precipitate&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=11 November 2017|language=en}}</ref> Another variant called red KPs may be seen in hemorrhagic uveitis.
